nton looking at the cosy cardigans in muted shades of grey, beige or sugary pastels. \"My mother would have worn any of these classic items but I won't be seen dead in them.\"</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-426643371'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/9/1389254782763/MS-cardigans-at-the-Hollo-009.jpg' alt='M&S cardigans at the Holloway Road store' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>M&S cardigans at the Holloway Road store</figcaption></figure><p>It wasn't always like this. A generation ago the nation shopped at Marks and Spencer, a retail empire whose (now defunct) <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/674973.stm\" title=\"\">St Michael logo</a> made it an institution. \"It used to be top of the list for clothes shopping for the whole population,\" says Hinton, who remembers when everyone in her office wore the same M&amp;S linen shirt in a different shade.</p><p>These days, office workers go to Next, a brand created in 1982 that is expected to make bigger profits this year than its 130-year rival for the first time ever. Next had a great Christmas, with sales up 12% on last year as shoppers snapped up its festive jumpers. \"Next has got a very clearly defined customer – the 25-45 year old and some either side,\" says Hinton. \"They just keep targeting that age group and they do it well.\" She credits Next for weaning itself off safe basics, with fashionable lines that have broadened its appeal.</p><p>M&amp;S is no stranger to the fashion pages. The 2014 spring-summer collection, from <a href=\"http://http://www.theguardian.com/business/2012/jul/20/belinda-earl-m-and-s-style-director\" title=\"\">style director Belinda Earl</a> –  floral print bomber jackets and brilliant white shirts and trousers – <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2013/11/13/belinda-earl-launches-second-marks-and-spencer-collection\" title=\"\">was trailed in Vogue</a>. The glossies whipped up a fuss over <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2013/oct/14/pink-coat-fashion-buy-ask-hadley\" title=\"\">a pink coat</a> in Earl's Autumn collection. But such runway-inspired designs are thin on the ground at Holloway Road, with its generous supply of floral nightgowns and sensible cardigans.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-426643369'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/9/1389255519883/MS-nightwear-at-Holloway--008.jpg' alt='M&S nightwear at Holloway Road' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>M&S nightwear at Holloway Road</figcaption></figure><p>\"[This] should be a good [profitable] store because there is a high density of population and there is not a lot else on offer.\"  But its residents are younger than the national average and Hinton is struck by the disconnect between the old-fashioned range and the younger women rifling through the sale rack.  The only range clearly targeted at younger shoppers in this store is Indigo: casual floral tops and cosy jumpers for people who might shop at Fat Face, but without \"the energy and excitement \" necessary.</p><p>In many ways, M&amp;S has fallen victim to the curse of dominance, an affliction shared by another middle-of-the road giant – Tesco. \"If you are the market leader and you have so many stores, it is a real problem in a market that's not growing, to generate more and more sales and attract new people.\"</p><p>Things look brighter at M&amp;S food. Sales remain robust, despite tougher than ever competition from Waitrose, another winner in the Christmas battle for the nation's wallets. But M&amp;S food is  more a place for treats and top-up shops, rather than the weekly shop, Hinton says.</p><p>Ultimately, M&amp;S boss Marc Bolland will not be judged on teatime treats and meal deals, but clothing. Hinton thinks he has another three months to prove his turnaround strategy will work before shareholders start grumbling.</p><p>But harder questions are down the road. M&amp;S has around 770 UK stores, \"far too many\" for an online future, Hinton thinks. And with its limited appeal to younger shoppers, M&amp;S is unlikely ever to return to its glory days: \"There are people in their 20s, 30s and 40s who don't shop there anymore – and this is a fierce market.\"</p>","headline":"M&amp;S store revamps may not be enough, analyst says","trailText":"<p>Products must also appeal to the new style-conscious M&amp;S customer, Conlumino retail analyst says</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3yy8m","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/8/1389204146281/Marks--Spencer--003.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/8/1389204146281/Marks--Spencer--003.jpg","wordcount":"687","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"426604519","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8531726","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Jennifer Rankin","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-09T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2023213","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-12T07:01:06Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/09/marks-and-spencer-store-revamps-turnaround-bid","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/2014/jan/09/marks-and-spencer-store-revamps-turnaround-bid","tags":[{"id":"business/marksspencer","webTitle":"Marks & Spencer","type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/marksspencer","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/marksspencer","references":[]},{"id":"business/retail","webTitle":"Retail industry","type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/retail","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/b