tionDate":"2014-01-02T19:08:14Z","sectionName":"Business","sectionId":"business","id":"business/2014/jan/02/debenhams-chief-executive-under-pressure-profit-warning","fields":{"standfirst":"Poor festive sales at department store has already claimed scalp of finance director, who will leave on 7 February","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-01-03T00:06:25Z","body":"<p>Debenhams' chief executive, Michael Sharp, is under mounting pressure to turn around the department store group's performance after its finance director, Simon Herrick, was forced to resign in the wake of this week's profit warning.</p><p>The group's share price rose 2.8% to 75p as it was announced that Herrick would leave the business on 7 February.</p><p>He will receive a payoff of £490,000, equivalent to a year's salary and benefits, if he does not find a new job within a year. Herrick is also in line for up to £10,000 to cover legal fees incurred negotiating his departure.</p><p>Herrick's departure followed Wednesday's profits warning, prompted by heavy discounting at Debenhams over the festive period, and fury among suppliers over a demand, penned by Herrick, for a 2.5% \"Santa tax\" discount on goods days before Christmas.</p><p>However, the finance director's fate is thought to have been already sealed after a series of problems last year including an earlier profit warning last spring and a £25m hit for refurbishing the chain's leading store, on London's Oxford Street.</p><p>Some analysts, however, suggested that Herrick had been made a scapegoat and that Debenhams' true problems lay with its trading strategy.</p><p>Clive Black, an analyst at Shore Capital, said: \"Debenhams may be guilty of not listening to its customers and moving away from what they want it to be in a drive for profit margin.\"</p><p>He suggested it was relying too heavily on own-label merchandise, such as its Designers at Debenhams ranges, which is more profitable but arguably less desirable than third-party brands.</p><p>Black said: \"With Simon Herrick out of the way, if there isn't any improvement, it will be interesting to see how Debenhams' management evolves.\"</p><p>Freddie George, a retail analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald, said he believed Sharp's position was secure for the time being, but that Debenhams had potentially taken a mis-step by discounting early so that it did not get the full benefit of a late rush in sales enjoyed by its rivals House of Fraser and John Lewis.</p><p>Strong sales growth in the run-up to Christmas was reported by House of Fraser as the department store's owners look to offload the business in a private sale or stock market launch this year.</p><p>Underlying sales rose 4.3% in the nine weeks to 28 December – the company's \"best ever\" Christmas period – driven by a near-58% rise in online sales, with beauty products a particular success. Stores also saw a strong 3% rise in sales in three weeks to 28 December.</p><p>\"We are pleased to report another record performance despite a more competitive environment,\" said the chief executive, John King. He added that the company expected to report further growth in full-year earnings and finish its financial year with net debt lower than the £157m reported in 2013.</p><p>The positive performance will boost House of Fraser's hopes of securing a deal with Galeries Lafayette, the French department store group. The pair are in talks until the end of January. If the discussions fail the UK chain is expected to attempt a return to the stock market after more than seven years in private&nbsp;hands.</p><p>However, analysts questioned whether the group had been able to lift its percentage gross margin on each pound of sales, a measure that would indicate the level of discounting behind its sales growth.</p><p>While the company said its total cash gross margin, a measure of overall profitability, was up 8.7% compared with last year, Tony Shiret, a retail analyst at Espirito Santo, said: \"The position on discounting is not entirely clear.\"</p><p>King said he could not reveal the percentage gross margin but insisted that it was up, driven by an increase in the proportion of own-label clothes on offer, and a reduced amount of discounting compared with last year. He said House of Fraser had also benefited from selling aspirational brands such as Ralph Lauren and Barbour. He said the company had also been able to manage its stocks well, with fewer unsold goods on the books after Christmas than ever before.</p><p>The fashion and homewares chain Next is expected to report reasonably strong figures on Friday. Marks &amp; Spencer, which reports on 9 January, is thought to have had to discount more heavily than last year to win sales. A grim Christmas would add to the pressure its chief executive, Marc Bolland, is already under.</p>","headline":"Debenhams chief executive under pressure after profit warning","trailText":"Poor festive sales at department store has already claimed scalp of finance director, who will leave on 7 February","newspaperPageNumber":"27","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3yhht","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/2/1388689640767/A-shopper-at-Debenhams-in-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/2/1388689640767/A-shopper-at-Debenhams-in-006.jpg","wordcount":"710","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"426163073","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8506667","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Sarah Butler","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-03T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2020536","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-05T19:08:14Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/02/debenhams-chief-executive-under-pressure-profit-warning","apiUrl":"http://internal